observations.recommendation:
We recommended that the LDRRMO:

Evaluate the unutilized balances of the current year’s five per cent LDRRMF, continuing LDRRMF, and the unexpended LDRRMF transferred to the TF books;

Anticipate and promptly address issues and concerns affecting the efficient and effective implementation of LDRRM PPAs to avoid delays or non-implementation;

Ensure efficient and effective implementation of all programmed and reprogrammed projects during the budget year to optimize the fund’s utilization and warrant that goals and objectives of reducing disaster risk and enhancing disaster preparedness and response capabilities be achieved.

We recommended that the Management:

Demand payment from the LGU personnel identified per Municipal Social Welfare and Development Office (MSWDO) records of their collections from the creditors of Self-Employment Assistance;

In the meantime, make the necessary adjustments to present in the books the actual receivables per MSWDO records and reclassify the receivables pertaining to the unremitted collections of LGU personnel to Due from Officers and Employees Account;

Require the Municipal Agriculturist to evaluate the collectability of each receivables pertaining to livelihood assistance; and

Make the necessary request for write-off of receivables for those deemed uncollectable.

We recommended that the Inventory Committee and the Municipal Accountant:
Conduct a physical count and assessment of all public infrastructure assets of the LGU including assets that were constructed before 2016, and make the necessary reconciliation and recognition in the books;
Include in the next physical count of PPEs and RPCPPE the Land, Land Improvements, Building and Other Structures accounts.

We recommended that the LDRRMO:
Evaluate the unutilized balances of the current year’s five per cent LDRRMF, continuing LDRRMF, and the unexpended LDRRMF transferred to the Trust Fund books;
Anticipate and promptly address issues and concerns affecting the efficient and effective implementation of LDRRM PPAs to avoid delays or non-implementation;
Maximize LDRRMF utilization by focusing on PPAs requiring the highest priority in terms of urgency and/or impact on the four thematic areas of Disaster Risk Reduction and Management and consider the needs of the time, such as the COVID-19 emergency; and
Ensure efficient and effective implementation of all programmed and reprogrammed projects during the budget year to optimize the fund’s utilization and warrant that goals and objectives of reducing disaster risk and enhancing disaster preparedness and response capabilities be achieved.

We recommended that the Municipal Treasurer:
Maintain one permanent record book per accountable form;
Ensure that the actual series of accountable forms/official receipts are the same as the series indicated in the permanent record book and check the accuracy of its sequence;
Indicate in the permanent record book the name and title of the officer or employee to whom such accountable forms have been given;
Indicate in the permanent record book the required column headings per LTOM, such as but not limited to 1) Booklet Number/Quantity (in case of official receipt without money value); 2) Serial Number/Total Value (in case of official receipt with money value); 3) data on the invoice number and date, the date the accountable forms were received; and 4) the quantity; and
Correctly filled out the Column provided for ‘Date reported totally used, sold, issued’ of the record book once the stub accountable form is handed over.

We recommended the Management to:

Demand payment from the LGU personnel identified per Municipal Social Welfare and Development Office (MSWDO) records of their collections from the creditors of Self-Employment Assistance (SEA);

In the meantime, make the necessary adjustments to present in the books the actual receivables per MSWDO records and reclassify the receivables pertaining to the unremitted collections of LGU personnel to Due from Officers and Employees Account;

Require the Municipal Agriculturist to evaluate the collectability of each receivables pertaining to livelihood assistance;

Make the necessary request for write-off of receivables for those deemed uncollectable; and

Henceforth, ensure that LGU programs similar in nature have well defined collection policy and active monitoring of receivables.

We recommended the Management to:

Require the Municipal Assessor’s Office to conduct property valuation in the Municipality to facilitate the computation of RPT and SET based on fair market value of the properties;

Require the OIC-MT to furnish the Municipal Accountant the list of taxable properties in the beginning of the year in order to setup RPT and SET Receivables in the books;

Require the  OIC-MT on the timely transfer of SET from General Fund (GF) to Special Education Fund (SEF);

Require the Municipal Accountant to ensure the accuracy of computation and entries in both the GF (RPT) and SEF (SET); and

Require the Municipal Accountant to reconcile differences between RPT and SET Receivables and its Deferred Income Counterpart to the extent the current workforce allows and ensure that no further variances will accumulate between the accounts.

We recommended the Management to:

Prospectively require the BAC to strictly comply with the provisions of R-IRR of R.A. No. 9184;
Provide the Municipal Accountant basis to prepare necessary journal entries for reclassification of portion of building account to furniture and fixtures and office equipment.

We recommend the Management to:
Demand payment from the LGU personnel identified per MSWDO records of their collections from the creditors of SEA;
In the meantime, make the necessary adjustments to present in the books the actual receivables per MSWDO records and reclassify the receivables pertaining to the unremitted collections of LGU personnel to Due from Officers and Employees Account;
Require the Municipal Agriculturist to evaluate the collectability of each receivables pertaining to livelihood assistance;
Make the necessary request for write-off of receivables for those deemed uncollectable; and
Henceforth, ensure that LGU programs similar in nature have well defined collection policy and active monitoring of receivables.

We recommended the Management to:
Require the MAO to conduct property valuation in the Municipality to facilitate the computation of RPT and SET based on fair market value of the properties;
Require the OIC-MT to furnish the Municipal Accountant the list of taxable properties in the beginning of the year in order to setup RPT and SET Receivables in the books;
Require the  OIC-MT on the timely transfer of SET from GF to SEF;
Require the Municipal Accountant to ensure the accuracy of computation and entries in both the GF (RPT) and SEF (SET); and
Require the Municipal Accountant to reconcile differences between RPT and SET Receivables and its Deferred Income Counterpart to the extent the current workforce allows and ensure that no further variances will accumulate between the accounts.

We recommended the Management to:
Prospectively require the BAC to strictly comply with the provisions of R-IRR of R.A. No. 9184;
Provide the Audit Team with the supporting documents and valid justification that will establish the technical capability of the supplier to deliver the above-mentioned furniture and fixtures and office equipment;
Provide valid justification for our review and evaluation on why the furniture and fixtures and office equipment were considered as direct cost which were used and included in the computation of Profit, VAT, and OCM of the ABC in order to avoid suspension or disallowance in audit; and
Provide the Municipal Accountant basis to prepare necessary journal entries for reclassification of portion of building account to furniture and fixtures and office equipment.
